  "prompt": "What are the hardest puzzles asked in interview?",
  "response": "Some of the hardest puzzles asked in technical and consulting interviews are designed to test your problem-solving skills, analytical thinking, and creativity. Here are a few examples that are particularly challenging:\n\n1. **The Five Pirates Puzzle**:\n   - Five pirates of different ages have to divide 100 gold coins among themselves. The oldest pirate proposes the division, and all pirates (including the proposer) vote on it. If at least half of them agree, the division is accepted; otherwise, the proposer is thrown overboard, and the next oldest pirate proposes a new division. Pirates are very rational and want to maximize their coins while minimizing the chance of dying. How will the coins be divided?\n\n2. **The 100 Prisoners and Light Bulb Puzzle**:\n   - There are 100 prisoners in solitary confinement. There is a central room with a light bulb that is initially off. Every day, one of the prisoners is selected uniformly at random to enter the room. While in the room, the prisoner can toggle the light bulb or leave it as is. Each prisoner has an opportunity",
